# License

The Agentic Development Protocol (ADP) is open. It is dual-licensed so the
*standard* can spread freely while the *tooling* stays maximally reusable.

Copyright (c) 2026 Guillermo Blanco.

## Documentation & specification — CC BY 4.0

All prose, specifications, diagrams, and written/visual materials are licensed
under the **Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License (CC BY 4.0)**.
Full text: `LICENSE-DOCS-CC-BY-4.0.txt` · https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/

This covers (non-exhaustively):

- `current/PROTOCOL.md` (the canonical spec) and `current/README.md`
- all `.md` documentation inside `current/template/docs/` and `current/template/.agentic-protocol/`
- diagrams and images distributed with the protocol

You may share and adapt these materials, including commercially, **provided you
give attribution**: "Agentic Development Protocol (ADP) by Guillermo Blanco,
CC BY 4.0, https://github.com/kikenandez/agentic-development-protocol".

## Code, scripts & templates — MIT

All source code is licensed under the **MIT License**.
Full text: `LICENSE-CODE-MIT.txt`

This covers (non-exhaustively):

- everything under `current/scripts/` (`init.sh`, `wire-sync.sh`, `adp_metrics.py`, `generate_map.py`)
- shell hooks under `current/template/.claude/hooks/`
- CI workflows under `current/template/.github/`
- config/wire/template files installed into a target repo (`.adp/`, `.claude/settings.json`, etc.)

## Which applies to a given file?

Documentation and specification text → CC BY 4.0. Executable code, scripts,
hooks, config, and machine-readable templates → MIT. When a file could be read
either way, the more permissive MIT terms apply to the code portions and CC BY
4.0 to the prose. If you need certainty for a specific file, open a GitHub Issue.

## Trademarks

"ADP" and "Agentic Development Protocol" name the standard. The licenses above
grant copyright permissions, **not** trademark rights. Don't use the names to
imply endorsement or official status (see CC BY 4.0 §2(a)(6)). You may always
state factually that your work "implements" or "is based on" ADP.
